Table S1. Experimental measurements used to evaluate force field accuracy

2

Scalar Couplings of Ala5
For each force field, we performed 500-ns simulations of Ala5 and computed scalar couplings constants using two different sets of Karplus equations: one set8,56,57 from a study by Graf et al.,1 and a second set used in a study from Best et al.58 incorporating more recently derived coefficients16 for 3JHNC, 3JHNCB, and 3JHNHKarplus equations with lower error estimates. As a metric for the deviation from experiment, we use the conventional definition ofχ2, taking into account estimates of the errors produced by uncertainty in the Karplus equation coefficients:

2 ∑

,

(1)

where Jexp(i) is the ith experimental J-coupling, Jcalc(i) is the corresponding ith coupling computed using a Karplus equation, and i the estimated error in the predictions made by the Karplus equation. Table S2 compares the χ2 values obtained with each set of Karplus equations. A perfect force field would be expected to have a χ2 value <1. All force fields investigated here were parameterized using Ala5 scalar couplings or similar data and thus reproduce reasonably well the experimental scalar couplings. Simulations run with C36m, a03ws and a99SB-UCB have χ2 values less than 1 using either set of Karplus equation parameters, while a99SB-ILDN with TIP4P-D only has a χ2 value <1 when using the more recently derived coefficients. a99SB*-ILDN and C22* also show reasonably good agreement with experimental J-couplings.

