Table S21. Comparison of calculated RMSD from experimental chemical shift measurements and number of NOE violations for 10-µs simulations of 41 proteins described in Mao et al.61 Chemical shift RMSDs (CS) are reported in ppm. NOE violations are defined as interatomic distances that exceed distance restraints by >1 Å. Agreement with experimental values obtained from the lowest energy NMR structure is shown for comparison, but FF scores are calculated using only the agreement observed in MD simulations.

22

Discussion of the a99SB-disp Protein Force Field Parameterization Strategy
Starting from the Amber99SB*-ILDN-Q force field62 and the TIP4P-D water model, we attempted to find a minimal set of parameter changes that would enable a reasonably accurate description of the proteins in our training set. We choose to focus on three force field terms: i) the backbone torsion potential, which influences the relative stability of secondary structure elements; ii) the strength of a backbone-backbone LJ pair override, which strengthens the interaction between the backbone carbonyl oxygens and backbone amide hydrogen atoms; and iii) the strength of the water dispersion interactions, which modulates the dimensions of the disordered states, and is important for the stability of the folded states of proteins and helical states in disordered proteins.
Our optimization attempts consisted of two phases. In the first phase, we utilized a reweighting algorithm63 to generate torsion corrections targeting (AAQAA)3 helicity and Ala5 scalar couplings. These torsion optimizations applied both φ and ψ corrections, utilizing corrections with phases of 0° or 90°. We iteratively tested torsion corrections obtained from our reweighting algorithm until no further improvements were observed, which generally required 5–10 iterations. The same torsion corrections were applied to all residues except glycine and proline. After obtaining a converged set of torsion corrections, in the second phase of parameterization we expanded our training set to include extensive NMR and SAXS data sets for ubiquitin, GB3, drkN SH3, α-synuclein, ACTR, NTAIL MoRE, and NTAIL. We also ran constant-temperature simulations of villin and GTT, in order to check if both systems would still fold in simulations near their melting temperature.
We abandoned the use of the reweighting algorithm in the second phase of the optimization, because we found that extremely long simulations would be required at each iteration to obtain statistically meaningful estimates of the gradients in parameter space, and that the algorithm
23

would be highly sensitive to the relative weights of different experimental observables. In these second-phase rounds of optimization, having previously obtained a reasonable description of Ramachandran space as measured by Ala5 scalar couplings, we restricted further torsion modifications to 1D corrections on the order of 0.1–0.2 kcal mol−1 in the ψ torsions, which had a negligible effect on the agreement with the polyalanine scalar couplings. After running simulations of the proteins in our training set, we calculated the average understabilization or overstabilization of helical states in our test systems and applied ψ-torsion corrections, using phases of 0° and 90°, to the helical basin to correct the balance between helical and non-helical states.
Initially, we attempted to reparameterize the Amber99SB*-ILDN-Q force field with TIP4P-D water, with the goal of describing both folded and disordered states using torsion optimizations alone. We found, however, that force fields that yielded reasonable agreement for the helicity of (AAQAA)3, NTAIL MoRE, and drkN SH3 resulted in simulations of ACTR, α-synuclein, and NTAIL that contained too much helicity and experienced a hydrophobic collapse (Figure S3). This appeared to be due to a reciprocal stabilization of helical states and collapsed states in disordered proteins. These force fields also tended to destabilize GB3 and ubiquitin, by disrupting the stability of  sheets.
In a second attempt at optimization, we introduced a specific LJ pair value for the interaction between backbone carbonyl oxygen atoms and backbone amide hydrogen atoms and introduced a new water model, which we refer to as a99SB-disp water, with a slightly stronger C6 dispersion term (Table S19, Figure S13). In the first phase we initially set the new LJ parameters to a σ value of 1.5 Å and an ε value of 0.20 kcal mol−1, and again used a reweighting algorithm63 targeting (AAQAA)3 helicity and Ala5 scalar couplings to obtain a converged set of φ and ψ backbone torsion corrections using TIP4P-D water. We then in the second phase expanded our training set to include ubiquitin, GB3, drkN SH3, α-synuclein, ACTR, NTAIL MoRE, and NTAIL, as well as simulations of villin and GTT near their melting temperature, and introduced 0.1–
24

0.2 kcal mol−1 ψ corrections to adjust the stability of the helical basin, while optimizing the ε value of the LJ override (the σ value was kept constant at 1.5 Å).
In our search of parameter space, we found that we were unable to simultaneously reproduce the helicity of both (AAQAA)3 and helical disordered proteins with high accuracy, and we ultimately decided to sacrifice good agreement with (AAQAA)3 helicity in favor of more accurate descriptions of NTAIL MoRE, NTAIL, drkN SH3, ACTR, and α-synuclein. After arriving at an ε value of 0.30 kcal mol−1 for the LJ override from the iterative rounds of optimization described above and adopting a99SB-disp water, we completed our parameterization with a final round of optimization of 1D ψ corrections. The agreement with experiment for the proteins in our training set converged to within the statistical errors of sampling after seven iterations of 1D ψ corrections. We note that, due to the computational cost of obtaining sufficiently converged simulations of the proteins in our training set, our search for a set of improved parameters was not exhaustive. We also note that we saw evidence of degeneracy between the strength of our LJ pair potential correction and the magnitude of backbone ψ-torsion corrections.
Finally, we also introduced a series of side-chain torsion modifications targeting PDB rotamer distributions and QM energy scans, a reparameterization of the side-chain charges of aspartate, glutamate, and arginine residues to match the guanidinum acetate association constant,63 and a reparameterization of glycine backbone torsion angles targeting a PDB coil-library distribution.64,65 These changes slightly improved the accuracy of simulations of folded proteins and had negligible effect on the accuracy of simulations of disordered proteins in our training set.
The high level of accuracy obtained in simulations performed with a99SB-disp on the remainder of the benchmark set not used in parameter optimization suggests that the parameters presented here are reasonably transferable, and that they should enable accurate simulations of both folded and disordered protein states. We believe that including other parameters in further optimizations, such as a larger subset of the nonbonded terms and, possibly, starting the
25

optimization from a different force field, could result in an equally or even more accurate parameterization. This would, however, substantially increase the computational cost of iterative parameter refinement, and may require the addition of an even larger array of systems to the benchmark set.
