Figure S9. Comparison of simulated and experimental (black) values for A40. Helical (A) and β (B) propensities observed in simulations of A40. Black lines are experimental estimates from the program δ2d.74 Simulated and experimental 3JHNHαscalar couplings (C) and backbone NH RDCs (D). Force field color scheme is as used in Fig. S1.
47

Figure S10. Comparison of simulated and experimental (black) values for PaaA2. Helical (A) and β (B) propensities observed in simulations of PaaA2. Black lines are experimental estimates from a restrained ensemble model (PED-5AAA) calculated from experimental data.44 Simulated and experimental backbone NH RDCs (C). Force field color scheme is as used in Fig. S1, and cyan values are back-calculated from the restrained ensemble PED-5AAA.
48

Figure S11. Comparison of simulated and experimental (black) values for NTAIL. Helical (A) and β (B) propensities observed in simulations of NTAIL. Black lines are experimental estimates from a restrained ensemble model (PED-7AAC) calculated from experimental data.73 Simulated and experimental backbone NH RDCs (C). Force field color scheme is as used in Fig. S1, and cyan values are back-calculated from the restrained ensemble PED-7AAC.
49

Figure S12. Comparison of simulated and experimental (black) values for GCN4. Helical (A) and β (B) propensities observed in simulations of GCN4. Black lines are experimental estimates from the program δ2d.74 Simulated and experimental backbone amide NMR relaxation S2 order parameters. Force field color scheme is as used in Fig. S1.
50

Figure S13. Solubility of small molecules in different solvent models. Hydration free energy of small-molecule fragments in TIP3P (black), TIP4P-D (red), and a99SB-disp water (blue). Each fragment is a model for an amino acid side chain; the name of the corresponding amino acid is reported near each data point. N-methylacetamide (NMA) is a small molecule used as a model for the protein backbone. The RMSD between TIP3P and a99SB-disp water is 0.4 kcal mol−1. The RMSD between TIP4P-D and a99SB-disp water is 0.4 kcal mol−1. The RMSDs of TIP3P, TIP4P-D, and a99SB-disp to experiment are all 1.6 kcal mol−1. We note that relative to TIP4P-D, hydrophobic residues in a99SB-disp water are slightly less soluble, and hydrophilic residues are slightly more soluble.
51

Figure S14. Comparison of normalized force field scores for simulations of folded and disordered proteins run using the a99SB-disp force field initialized from the same starting structures with different sets of randomized velocities.
52

Figure S15. Comparison of fraction of NOE violations for 10-µs simulations of 41 proteins described in Mao et al.61 NOE violations are defined as interatomic distances that exceed distance restraints by >1 Å. We note that three of the proteins (2L3A, 1RZW, and 2KW5) have an unusually large fraction of violations. 1RZW and 2KW5 are homodimers in X-ray structures, but were considered as monomers in the NMR experiment. 2L3A was solved as a dimer, and has two long, loosely packed C-terminal tails, which were disordered in simulation and contributed to most of the observed violations. Removing these three proteins from the dataset does not change the overall conclusions, as all force fields tested performed similarly on these structures.
53

Figure S16. Thermodynamics of villin folding in simulations run with the a99SB-disp protein force field and a99SB-disp water (blue), the a99SB-disp protein force field and TIP3P water (red), and the a99SB-disp protein force field and TIP4P-D water (green). The experimental melting curve is shown in black. The fraction of folded conformations as a function of temperature is reported in panel A; the unfolding enthalpy is reported in panel B. Cold denaturation is observed when the unfolding enthalpy becomes negative.
54

Table S26. Comparison of calculated RMSD from experimental chemical shift measurements and NOE violations for 10-µs simulations of 41 proteins described in Mao et al.61 Chemical shift RMSDs are reported in ppm. NOE violations are defined as interatomic distances that exceed distance restraints by >1 Å. We note that three of the proteins (2L3A, 1RZW and 2KW5) have an unusually large fraction of violations. 1RZW and 2KW5 are homodimers in X-ray structures, but were considered as monomers in the NMR experiment. 2L3A was solved as a dimer and has two long, loosely packed C-terminal tails, which were disordered in simulations and contributed to most of the observed violations. Removing these three proteins from the dataset does not change the conclusions, as all force fields tested performed similarly on these structures. N is the number of residues, and dimers are indicated with an *.

